Rating: 0
For the cook from Peoria. A brine is a process of soaking meat in a liquid that has been heavily salted. It is good used with pork, chicken and turkey to greatly increase texture and flavor. There are a couple recipes that use brines in epicurious. Hope this helps.

Rating: 0
To Peoria: You're going to get at least 5 responses to your question, but I'll put in my $.02. Brining usually means soaking large cuts of meats in a solution consisting of salted water that often includes, sugar, spices and herbs as well. It serves to tenderize and flavor the meat (usually large cuts i.e.: roasts, whole turkeys, hams, etc.) The method has risks, however, unless you have researched it. You must pay special attention to temperature, and sometimes means a lot of work. I highly recommend it, however. It's amazing how much better well-brined meats are. I will never cook a T'giving bird again without brining. There is plenty of info on this site about brining, as well as other sites on the internet. Bon Appetit.

