Rating: 4
This was the absolute hit of my recent celebration. I did, however, make at least 1 1/2 times the dressing, but next time will at least double the recipe. Everyone had seconds, even my daughter and she rarely eats any meat. The meat was tender enough to cut with a fork, the smells in my home were beyond compare. Thank you for this wonderful website. I shall visit it often.

Rating: 4
This will be one of my special meals. It was wonderful. I took the advice of others here and used a low-strength brine for around 5 hours. Also, I added about one cup of dried tart cherries to the stuffing. The meat was tasty and tender, not salty and the stuffing was delicious. I served it with a spinach salad, and Pinot Noir.

Rating: 4
I used a different recipe for the roast and sauce (and am sorry that I did). The stuffing was outstanding!!! I just wish that I had made more. I had 8 adults and there was enough for everyone to just have one helping. It was very disappointing not to have leftovers the next day. Next time I will double the recipe and cook the extra in a dish with the roast.

Rating: 4
I wanted to make an unusual turkey for my French friends who had never experienced Thanksgiving before. I found this recipe and decided just to use the stuffing alone, so prepared it for Thanksgiving. I put the stuffing in the turkey cavity and roasted it in the oven (I also added stuffing around the turkey in the pan about a half hour before removing the turkey from the oven.) Well... it was just heavenly. My French friends couldn't believe it and asked for more. In fact, I think they far preferred it to the turkey!

Rating: 3
I am using this for a cooking class. I would make it again...however I would brine the pork to keep it from drying out. Pulled it from the oven at 155, but it still was a little flavorless. Have had great results with pork brine, will try next time. The glazed apples did not brown but burnt. Would recommend roasting rather then broiling.